{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/17-rules-of-thumb-for-building-a-neural-network-93356f9930af", "time": 1682997353.230989, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/17-rules-of-thumb-for-building-a-neural-network-93356f9930af/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Rules-of-thumb for building a Neural Network | by Chitta Ranjan | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Rules-of-thumb for building a Neural Network", "description": "Deep Learning provides a wide variety of models. With them, we can build extremely accurate predictive models. However, with the wide variety and a multitude of setting parameters it may be daunting\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.understandingdeeplearning.com", "anchor_text": "Understanding Deep Learning", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/extreme-rare-event-classification-using-autoencoders-in-keras-a565b386f098", "anchor_text": "Extreme Rare Event Classification using Autoencoders in Keras", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/step-by-step-guide-to-install-tensorflow-2-0-67bc73e79b82", "anchor_text": "Step-by-Step Guide to Install Tensorflow 2", "paragraph_index": 13}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/extreme-rare-event-classification-using-autoencoders-in-keras-a565b386f098", "anchor_text": "Extreme Rare Event Classification using Autoencoders in Keras", "paragraph_index": 26}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/simplified-math-behind-dropout-in-deep-learning-6d50f3f47275", "anchor_text": "Understanding Dropout with the Simplified Math behind it", "paragraph_index": 27}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/lstm-autoencoder-for-extreme-rare-event-classification-in-keras-ce209a224cfb", "anchor_text": "LSTM Autoencoder for Extreme Rare Event Classification in Keras", "paragraph_index": 28}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/build-the-right-autoencoder-tune-and-optimize-using-pca-principles-part-i-1f01f821999b", "anchor_text": "Build the right Autoencoder \u2014 Tune and Optimize using PCA principles. Part I", "paragraph_index": 29}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/build-the-right-autoencoder-tune-and-optimize-using-pca-principles-part-ii-24b9cca69bd6", "anchor_text": "Build the right Autoencoder \u2014 Tune and Optimize using PCA principles. Part II", "paragraph_index": 30}, {"url": "http://www.understandingdeeplearning.com", "anchor_text": "www.understandingdeeplearning.com", "paragraph_index": 32}], "all_paragraphs": ["<<Download the free book, Understanding Deep Learning, to learn more>>", "Deep Learning provides a wide variety of models. With them, we can build extremely accurate predictive models. However, with the wide variety and a multitude of setting parameters it may be daunting to find a starting point.", "In this article, we will find a starting point for building a Neural Network, more specifically a Multilayer Perceptron as an example but most of it is generally applicable.", "The idea here is to go over the thumb-rules to build a first neural network model. Tune and optimize this first model if it performs reasonably (minimally acceptable accuracy). Otherwise, it is better to look in the problem, data, or a different approach.", "Neural Network has advanced tremendously with CNNs, RNNs, etc. and several subtypes within each of them developed over time. With each development we have successfully improved our prediction capabilities.", "But at the same time, we have successfully made it harder to find a starting point for model building.", "Each model has its own sky-reaching claims. With so many billboards around, it is easy to get distracted.", "In the following, we will sail through the distractions by using a few rules-of-thumb to build a first model.", "We have a variety of neural networks. Among them, a multilayer perceptron is the \u201chello world\u201d of Deep Learning. And, therefore, a good place to start when you are learning about or developing a new model in Deep Learning.", "Following are the thumb-rules for building an MLP. However, most of them are applicable on other Deep Learning models.", "I have implemented the MLP Neural Network on the paper sheet break data set I have used in my previous articles (see Extreme Rare Event Classification using Autoencoders in Keras).", "In this implementation, we will see examples for the elements we mentioned in the above rules-of-thumb.", "The implementation is done in TensorFlow 2. I highly recommend migrating to TensorFlow 2, if not already. It has all the simplicity of Keras and significantly better computational efficiency.", "Follow Step-by-Step Guide to Install Tensorflow 2 for installation.", "In the following, I am not attempting to find the best model. The idea is to learn the implementations. No step is skipped to favor brevity. Instead, the steps are verbose to help the reader apply them directly.", "To test whether you are with the correct TensorFlow version, run this,", "This is a timeseries data in which we have to predict the event (y = 1) ahead in time. In this data, consecutive rows are 2 minutes apart. We will shift the labels in column y by 2 rows to do a 4 minute ahead prediction.", "Remove the time column now. It won\u2019t be required from here.", "And separate the X and y.", "We will develop a FalsePositiveRate() metric that we will use in each model below.", "We will write two plot function to visualize the progress in loss, and accuracy measures. We will use them for the models built below.", "See the model fitting loss and accuracies (recall and FPR) progress.", "Define the class weights as mentioned in the rules of thumb.", "Now, we will train the model.", "We use the selu activation that got popular due its self-normalizing properties.", "Read my other articles for more Deep Learning understanding, models, and implementations.", "Extreme Rare Event Classification using Autoencoders in Keras.", "Understanding Dropout with the Simplified Math behind it.", "LSTM Autoencod